.TH SNIPROXY 8 "16 Mar 2026" "SNIProxy manual" "sniproxy"

.SH NAME

SNIProxy \- transparent session based TLS, HTTP, DTLS, XMPP, and Minecraft proxy

.SH SYNOPSIS

\fBsniproxy\fR [ -\fBc\fR \fIconfig\fR ] [ -\fBf\fR ] [ -\fBg\fR ] [ -\fBt\fR ]
[ -\fBn\fR \fIfile-descriptor-limit\fR ] [ -\fBV\fR ] [ -\fBT\fR \fImin-tls-version\fR ] [ -\fBd\fR ]

.SH DESCRIPTION

Proxies incoming HTTP, TLS, DTLS, XMPP, and Minecraft Java Edition
connections, including HTTP/2 requests, based on the hostname contained in
the initial request. For TCP protocols (TLS, HTTP, XMPP, Minecraft) the
hostname is extracted from the initial TCP stream. For DTLS the hostname is
extracted from the SNI extension in the UDP ClientHello datagram, enabling
proxying of WebRTC, OpenConnect VPN, and other UDP/DTLS protocols by
hostname without decryption. This enables HTTPS name-based virtual hosting
to separate backend servers without installing the private key on the proxy
machine\&. By default TLS 1.2 (and newer) client hellos are
accepted\&.

For security reasons the configuration file must not be readable or
executable by group/other users. sniproxy verifies the permissions after
opening the file and aborts startup if it detects broader access.

.SH OPTIONS

.TP
-c \fIconfig\fR
Specify configuration file to use. The default is
/etc/sniproxy\&.conf\&.

.TP
-f
Do not daemonize, and run in foreground\&.

.TP
-g
Allow group-read (0640) permissions on the configuration file\&.
By default sniproxy requires mode 0600\&. This flag relaxes the check
to 0640 so the unprivileged process can re-read the config on SIGHUP
reload\&. The config file should be owned by root with its group set to
the sniproxy user group (e\&.g\&. root:_sniproxy)\&. A security warning is
logged at startup when this flag is used\&.

.TP
-t
Test configuration and exit\&. Parses the configuration file and reports
whether it is valid without starting the proxy\&.

.TP
-n \fIfile-descriptor-limit\fR
Specify the maximum file descriptor resource limit\&. SNIProxy will
attempt to set the maximum file descriptor limit to the value
specified\&.

.TP
-V
Print the version of SNIProxy and exit\&.

.TP
-T \fImin-tls-version\fR
Set the minimum TLS ClientHello version that will be accepted. The
value must be one of 1.0, 1.1, 1.2, or 1.3, and controls both the
legacy version field and the supported_versions extension. The default
is 1.2.

.TP
-d
Enable verbose resolver debug logging to stderr and the error log to aid DNS troubleshooting\&.

.SH SIGNALS

.TP
.B SIGHUP
Reopen log files and reload the configuration file\&. Existing
connections continue using their original routing; new connections
use the updated configuration\&.

.TP
.B SIGUSR1
Dump all active TCP connections and UDP sessions to a temporary file
for debugging\&. The file is created in
.I $XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/sniproxy\fR,
.I /var/run/sniproxy\fR,
or
.I /tmp/sniproxy-<uid>
(tried in that order)\&.

.TP
.B SIGINT\fR, \fBSIGTERM
Shut down gracefully\&.

.SH SANDBOXING
On OpenBSD,
\fBsniproxy\fR
uses
\fBpledge\fR(2)
and
\fBunveil\fR(2)
to restrict each process to the minimum set of system calls and
filesystem paths required\&.
.PP
On FreeBSD,
\fBsniproxy\fR
uses Capsicum capability mode
(\fBcap_enter\fR(2))
and per-fd rights
(\fBcap_rights_limit\fR(2))
to confine each process after initialization\&.
Directories needed for config reload and log rotation are pre-opened
so that
\fBopenat\fR(2)
works inside capability mode\&.
Set
.B SNIPROXY_DISABLE_CAPSICUM
in the environment to disable Capsicum sandboxing\&.
.PP
On Linux,
\fBsniproxy\fR
uses seccomp-bpf to restrict available system calls per process\&.

.SH "SEE ALSO"
.PP
\fBsniproxy.conf\fR(5)
